description: Corallorhiza maculata, but faded, I believe. Found in Stony Creek campground, along the Generals Highway just outside of Sequoia National Park.

Sarcodes sanguinea. This might win the Coolest Plant of the Trip award. First time I saw it out the window of the car I had one of my near-fatal head turnings. It's a giant flaming magenta saprophyte. I mean, that's practically worth crashing for, right? Saprophytes get their energy exclusively from fungal associations in the soil, so basically they eat decomposing things instead of photosynthesizing. If you're from the East Coast, they're like Indian pipes. Yeah, the coralroot is also saprophytic, but not quite as mind-blowing. Found in Stony Creek campground, along the Generals Highway just outside of Sequoia National Park.

Meadow in between Grant Grove and King's Canyon.  Geotag (5900') is a pretty good guess.  Thought at first that this was Spearmint, but the range & habitat data just weren't adding up, so I looked further.

Meadow in between Grant Grove and King's Canyon.  Geotag is a pretty good guess.

I think this is L. latifolius, given the broad leaves with small numbers of leaflets, relative lack of hairiness, and streamside habitat.  Other possibilities are L. albicaulis & L. microcarpus var. densiflorus. L. latifolius var. columbianus and L. albicaulis both have single herbarium records from Kings Canyon; those are the only decent matches anywhere in the area.

I think I'm just about to give up on amateur attempts to ID photos of 'difficult' taxa via Jepson Manual descriptions plus herbarium records.  Seems like I'm likely to get it wrong as often as to get it right!
Meadow in between Grant Grove and King's Canyon.  Geotag (5900') is a pretty good guess.

Meadow in between Grant Grove and King's Canyon. Geotag (5900') is a pretty good guess. Not sure I have 100% ruled out CA Goldenrod (S. californica), but it definitely has >11 ray flowers (the upper limit for californica), the ecology is a better match for canadensis ("meadows, thickets") than for californica (woodland margins, grassland, disturbed soils), & there are multiple 'geotagged' herbarium accessions for canadensis from this site & similar nearby meadows, none for californica (closest 2 are in Kings Cyn itself, lower & drier). Not the best photo, but posting it as an ID shot. California species resources: Jepson Interchange (Jepson Manual description & range map, photos from CalPhotos, herbarium accessions, etc.)
